#Download data

# Download the individual dataset
individual_data <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/01_chs/chs_individual.csv")

# Download the regional dataset
regional_data <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/USCbiostats/data-science-data/master/01_chs/chs_regional.csv")

#Merge Data by Location

combined_data <- merge(individual_data, regional_data, by = "townname")

#Check for duplicates

nrow_combined <- nrow(combined_data)
combined_data <- combined_data[!duplicated(combined_data), ]
nrow_after <- nrow(combined_data)

#Handle missing values

library(dplyr)

Attaching package: 'dplyr'
The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':

    filter, lag
The following objects are masked from 'package:base':

    intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(male, hispanic) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.numeric), ~ifelse(is.na(.), mean(., na.rm = TRUE), .))) %>%
  mutate(across(where(is.factor), ~ifelse(is.na(.), as.character(Mode(.)), .)))

#Create categorical variable named âobesity_levelâ

combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(obesity_level = case_when(
    bmi < 14 ~ "underweight",
    bmi >= 14 & bmi <= 22 ~ "normal",
    bmi > 22 & bmi <= 24 ~ "overweight",
    bmi > 24 ~ "obese"
  ))

#Summary table of BMI

summary_table <- combined_data %>%
  group_by(obesity_level) %>%
  summarize(min_bmi = min(bmi, na.rm = TRUE), 
            max_BMI = max(bmi, na.rm = TRUE),
            total_obs = n())

print(summary_table)
# A tibble: 4 Ã 4

3 overweight       22.0    24.0        87
4 underweight      11.3    14.0        35

#Create categorical variable âsmoke_gas_exposureâ

combined_data <- combined_data %>%
  mutate(smoke_gas_exposure = case_when(
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 1 ~ "Both",
    smoke == 1 & gasstove == 0 ~ "Smoke only",
    smoke == 0 & gasstove == 1 ~ "Gas only",
    TRUE ~ "Neither"
  ))

#Formulate a question #What is the association between BMI and FEV?

[1] 0.127529

There seems to be a positive relationship between BMI and FEV. The slope is 31.23 with a p-value that is less that .05. This means that for every increase in BMI, the FEV increases by 31.23 mL, which is a statistically significant increase.

library(ggplot2)


lm_pm25_model <- lm(`fev` ~ pm25_mass, data = combined_data)


ggplot(combined_data, aes(x = pm25_mass, y = `fev`)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "Linear Regression: FEV by PM2.5 Exposure",
    x = "PM2.5 Exposure",
    y = "FEV (ml)"
  ) +
  theme_minimal()
`geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

It seems that as PM2.5 exposure increases, FEV decreases. The linear regression shows a slope of -3.016 with a p-value of 0.011. This means that with every increase in a unit of pm25 mass, the FEV decreases by 3.016 mL, which was statistically significant.
